service_description: Separate to our TRA's we promote Neighbourhood Champions amongst our residents who we invite on monthly estate inspections. The TRA members are welcome to come on site visit and some are both members of the TRA and Neighbourhood Champions. All key sites in Tower Hamlets has an active action tracker which we keep and share with the residents providing updates on key actions/issues and repairs. We also have a minor improvement budget where the Neighbourhood Committee in the East will review and approve each proposal for improvement funding on our estates. The Neighbourhood Committee is made up of a group of residents from across Tower Hamlets, Newham and Barking and Dagenham. The chair for the current NC lives in Tower Hamlets and is also on our Resident Board. , The Redbrick TRA has been instrumental in the regeneration programme at New Union Wharf and the chair and sub-chair have been involved in regular meetings with us to ensure we comply with the offer document put in place by East Thames. , L&Q also sits on the board for ORT (Ocean Regeneration Trust) which works with the local community on the Ocean Estate and supports a number of community initiatives. The ORT board works closely with the TRA's and active resident groups across the Ocean Estate, Grand Union Place and the Feeder sites. , We also carry out joint reviews of service charges with the TRA and active resident groups before the finals are issued out to all residents. The collaborative approach with residents has been beneficial for both parties to ensure the costs we pass on have been audited by residents before sent out to the wider estate.

address: We currently have 11 x active Estate Boards/Residents Groups representing our Poplar HARCA Estates. The Estate Board/Resident groups are Aberfeldy, Bow Bridge, Brownfield, Burdett, Coventry Cross, Island Point, Lansbury North/South, Lansbury West, Leopold, Lincoln and Teviot. Estate Board/Resident Group meetings are held at Poplar HARCA's head office and at various Poplar HARCA Neighbourhood Centres throughout the year. Please contact Poplar HARCA's Estate Board Manager, Dave Tull, at dave.tull@poplarharca.co.uk for more details.
service_description: Our current 11 x Estate Boards/Resident Groups generally meet in the evening on a quarterly basis. The Estate Boards/Resident Groups are attended by local residents (up to a maximum of 24 people per Board) who act as a voice for the local community within Poplar HARCA. The Estate Boards/Resident Groups work in partnership with Poplar HARCA to ensure that residents’ voices are heard within the organisation in order to contribute towards: How services are being delivered ,  How services can be improved ,  Future plans, projects and initiatives ,  How to spend an allocated Estate minor works budget.  Our Estate Boards/Resident Groups have an advisory/consultative role on local service provision, Housing, Technical, Community and physical regeneration. The views of our resident groups are important, which are fed back to our main Boards to help us shape and deliver services going forward. Estate Boards/Gathering Groups are a great way for residents to get together as an effective representative voice for their local community.
category: Community Spaces, Arts & Culture, Housing & Support Services
